"AFT 1134":"after 1134","1164":"1164","1153":"1153","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1072":"1072","1129":"1129","1103":"1103","1125":"1125","1224":"1224","1114":"1114","1134":"1134","08 Apr 1140":"8 April 1140","Sint-Truiden, Limburg, Belgium":"Sint-Truiden, Limburg, Belgium","Sint-Truiden, Provincie Limburg, Flanders, Belgique":"Sint-Truiden, Limburg, Belgium","Duras, Limbourg, Belgique":"Duras, Limburg, Belgium","Duras, Sint-Truiden, Limburg, Vlaanderen, België":"Duras, Limburg, Belgium","Leuven, Vlaams-Brabant, Belgium":"Leuven, Flemish Brabant, Belgium","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Duras","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Normand, Michel, Pierre, Antoine, Camille, Emile, Jacques, Marcel, Philippe, Raoul.","French: topographic name for someone who lived in an isolated dwelling in the country rather than in a village, from Occitan <i>mas</i> ‘farmstead’ (see   Mas   1); or a habitational name for someone from Le Mas, the name of several places mainly in the southern part of France, named with the same word. It is formed with fused preposition and definite article <i>du</i> ‘from the’. This surname is also common in Haiti. Compare   Demos   and   Demoss  .","History: François Dumas from Nanteuil-en-Vallée in Charente, France, married Marguerite Foy in QC in 1667. — This surname is listed (independently and along with its altered forms <i>De Mos</i> and <i>De Moss</i>) in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."],"variants":[{"name":"Mas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Ramon, Francisco, Jose, Juan, Pedro, Jaime, Luis, Carlos, Raul, Ana, Angel, Aquiles.","Catalan and French (Occitan): topographic name for someone who lived in an isolated dwelling in the country, rather than in a village, from Catalan and Occitan <i>mas</i> ‘farmstead’ (from Late Latin <i>mansum</i>, <i>mansus</i>). Compare   Dumas  .","North German and Dutch: from a short form of the personal name   Thomas  . Compare   Maas   1 and   Mass  ."]},{"name":"Delmas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armelle, Fabienne.  Spanish Andres, Jose, Josue, Miguel, Ruben, Teodoro.","French (southern): variant of   Dumas  , a topographic name for someone from a remote, outlying farmstead.","Aragonese (<b>Delmàs</b>): cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Looz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["South German and Swiss German: regional (Alemannic) nickname from Middle High German <i>boese</i> ‘ridiculous person, low-standing servant’ or from an ancient Germanic personal name <i>Bozo</i> (see   Bosshart  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Bosshart","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Armin, Hans, Otto, Rudi.","Swiss German and South German: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>bōs</i> ‘bad, evil, wild, angry’ and <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, strong, brave’, or a derivative of a short form of the personal name   Burkhart   (see   Boss  ). Compare   Boshart   1 and   Buzzard   2."]},{"name":"Booze","meanings":["Possibly an Americanized form of German   Booz  ."]}]},{"name":"Othon","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Some translate Otho 'happy' and Otto 'rich;' but they would seem to be the same name, for Otho of Freysingen, son of Leopold, Margrave of Austria, and of Agnes, daughter of the Emperor Henry IV., is also called Otto. It was the surname of a Roman emperor, and of one of the Roscian family; It comes from Old German od, excelling, happy, fortunate."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Othon de Duras de Looz II was born in 1103, in Duras, Limburg, Belgium, his father, Giselbert Comte de Duras, was 31 and his mother, Oda Otto De Chiny, was 18. He married Berthe de Ribemont de Bouchain in 1129. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. His occupation is listed as avoué de saint-trond in Sint-Truiden, Limburg, Belgium. He died on 8 April 1140, in Sint-Truiden, Limburg, Belgium, at the age of 37."},"et":{"1103–08 Apr 1140":"1103–8. aprill 1140","1103–1140":"1103–1140","1114–1153":"1114–1153","1125–1164":"1125–1164","1130–1224":"1130–1224","1072–Male":"1072–Surnud","1085–1134":"1085–1134","AFT 1134":"pärast 1134","1164":"1164","1153":"1153","1130":"1130","1085":"1085","1140":"1140","1072":"1072","1129":"1129","1103":"1103","1125":"1125","1224":"1224","1114":"1114","1134":"1134","08 Apr 1140":"8. aprill 1140","Sint-Truiden, Limburg, Belgium":"Sint-Truiden, Limburg, Belgia","Sint-Tru